      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're right, my apologies! The calculation for the current is just as simple once you have the impedance. Since you have the total voltage ($V$) of 120V and the total impedance ($Z$) of 130 ohms, you find the current ($I$) using the AC version of Ohm's Law: $I = V / Z$.\n\nIn your case, $I = 120V / 130\\Omega$, which works out to approximately $0.923$ Amperes. Think of it like this: the resistance and the reactance don't just stack up like two piles of dirt; they are *orthogonal*, like two different types of muscle that have to work together to push the same heavy rock. If you just added $50 + 120 = 170$ ohms, you'd be calculating the *sum* of the components, which is only correct if they were in *parallel*, not in series. In a series circuit, the total opposition is the vector sum, which is why we use that square root trick—it finds the hypotenuse, the true total resistance to the flow.\n\nIt's a bit",
